5000|$|Law {{professor}} James Duane told New York {{magazine that}} Gowdy's assertion was [...] "extremely imaginative" [...] but [...] "mistaken," [...] because {{a person who}} is involuntarily summoned before a grand jury or a legislative body may selectively <b>invoke</b> <b>the</b> <b>right</b> to silence. Law professor Alan Dershowitz took a different view, arguing: [...] "You can't simply make statements about a subject and then plead the Fifth in response to questions about the very same subject," [...] and asserting, [...] "once you open the door to an area of inquiry, you have waived your Fifth Amendment right." ...|$|R
